    <div class="hero-section">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="hero-content">
                <div class="emergency-badge">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> URGENT ALERT
                </div>
                <h1 class="hero-title">5 Signs Your Septic Tank Needs Immediate Attention</h1>
                <p class="hero-subtitle">Don't wait for a costly disaster! These critical warning signs could save you thousands in emergency repairs and protect your family's health.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="main-content">
            <div class="content-section">
                <div class="stat-box">
                    <span class="stat-number">$3,000-$7,000</span>
                    <div class="stat-text">Average cost of emergency septic system replacement that could have been prevented with early detection</div>
                </div>

                <p class="intro-text">
                    Picture this: It's 2 AM on a Sunday morning, and you're awakened by the unmistakable smell of sewage wafting through your home. Your septic system has failed catastrophically, and you're facing thousands of dollars in emergency repairs, potential health hazards, and the nightmare of explaining to your family why they can't use the bathroom.
                </p>

                <p class="intro-text">
                    This scenario plays out for over 25,000 homeowners every year – but it doesn't have to be your story. The truth is, septic systems rarely fail without warning. They send clear distress signals weeks or even months before complete failure occurs.
                </p>

                <div class="image-placeholder">
                    <i class="fas fa-home"></i>
                    <span>Septic System Cross-Section Diagram Showing Warning Sign Locations</span>
                </div>

                <p class="intro-text">
                    As someone who has consulted with hundreds of homeowners dealing with septic emergencies, I've identified five critical warning signs that appear in 90% of all septic failures. Recognizing these signs early can mean the difference between a $200 maintenance call and a $5,000 emergency excavation.
                </p>

                <div class="warning-signs-grid">
                    <div class="warning-sign">
                        <div class="warning-header">
                            <div class="warning-number">1</div>
                            <h3 class="warning-title">Slow or Gurgling Drains Throughout Your Home</h3>
                        </div>
                        <div class="warning-content">
                            <p>When your septic tank approaches capacity or experiences a blockage, the first symptom you'll notice is slow-draining fixtures. This isn't just one sink or toilet – multiple drains throughout your home will start gurgling, bubbling, or draining sluggishly.</p>
                            
                            <div class="image-placeholder" style="height: 250px; margin: 25px 0;">
                                <i class="fas fa-sink"></i>
                                <span>Multiple Slow-Draining Fixtures in Home</span>
                            </div>

                            <p><strong>What's happening:</strong> Your septic tank is either full and needs pumping, or there's a blockage preventing proper flow to the drain field. The wastewater has nowhere to go, so it backs up into your plumbing system.</p>

                            <p><strong>The danger:</strong> This early warning sign often gets dismissed as a "minor plumbing issue." Homeowners typically try drain cleaners or call a plumber to snake individual drains. But when the problem is septic-related, these quick fixes are like putting a band-aid on a broken dam.</p>

                            <p><strong>Immediate action required:</strong> If multiple drains are affected simultaneously, especially the lowest fixtures in your home, contact a septic professional within 48 hours. Do NOT use chemical drain cleaners, as they can kill the beneficial bacteria in your septic system and make the problem worse.</p>

                            <div class="urgency-indicator">
                                <i class="fas fa-clock"></i> 48-Hour Response Window
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="warning-sign">
                        <div class="warning-header">
                            <div class="warning-number">2</div>
                            <h3 class="warning-title">Foul Odors Around Your Property</h3>
                        </div>
                        <div class="warning-content">
                            <p>A properly functioning septic system should be virtually odorless. If you're detecting sewage smells around your septic tank area, drain field, or even inside your home, your system is crying out for help.</p>

                            <div class="image-placeholder" style="height: 250px; margin: 25px 0;">
                                <i class="fas fa-nose"></i>
                                <span>Homeowner Detecting Septic Odors in Yard</span>
                            </div>

                            <p><strong>Where you'll smell it:</strong></p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Around the septic tank lid or access ports</li>
                                <li>Over the drain field area, especially after rain</li>
                                <li>Near plumbing vents on your roof</li>
                                <li>In your basement or lowest level of your home</li>
                                <li>Around floor drains or utility sinks</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p><strong>What causes septic odors:</strong> These smells indicate that anaerobic bacteria (the "bad" bacteria) are taking over your system. This happens when the system becomes overloaded, lacks proper ventilation, or when the natural bacterial balance is disrupted.</p>

                            <p><strong>Health risks:</strong> Septic gases contain hydrogen sulfide and methane, which can cause headaches, nausea, and respiratory irritation. In enclosed spaces, these gases can be dangerous or even fatal.</p>

                            <p><strong>Don't ignore it because:</strong> Many homeowners rationalize septic odors as "normal" or seasonal. The truth is, even a faint sewage smell indicates your system is struggling and needs professional attention.</p>

                            <div class="urgency-indicator">
                                <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Health Hazard - Act Immediately
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="warning-sign">
                        <div class="warning-header">
                            <div class="warning-number">3</div>
                            <h3 class="warning-title">Standing Water or Wet Spots Around the Drain Field</h3>
                        </div>
                        <div class="warning-content">
                            <p>Your drain field should absorb and filter wastewater underground. When you see persistent wet spots, standing water, or unusually lush grass growth over the drain field area, it means untreated sewage is surfacing – a serious health and environmental hazard.</p>

                            <div class="image-placeholder" style="height: 250px; margin: 25px 0;">
                                <i class="fas fa-tint"></i>
                                <span>Standing Water Over Septic Drain Field</span>
                            </div>

                            <p><strong>What to look for:</strong></p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Soggy ground that doesn't dry out, even in sunny weather</li>
                                <li>Standing pools of dark, foul-smelling water</li>
                                <li>Unusually green or lush grass growth in strips or patches</li>
                                <li>Spongy or squishy ground when you walk on it</li>
                                <li>Water that appears oily or has an unusual color</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p><strong>Root causes:</strong> Surface sewage indicates your drain field is either saturated, clogged, or failing. This could be due to:</p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Compacted soil from heavy vehicles or equipment</li>
                                <li>Root intrusion from trees or large shrubs</li>
                                <li>System overload from excessive water usage</li>
                                <li>Biomat buildup blocking soil absorption</li>
                                <li>Structural damage to distribution pipes</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p><strong>Environmental and health risks:</strong> Surface sewage contaminates groundwater, attracts disease-carrying insects, and poses serious health risks to children and pets. It can also contaminate nearby wells and water sources.</p>

                            <p><strong>Why this is critical:</strong> Once sewage surfaces, you're dealing with a failed system that requires immediate professional intervention. This is not a DIY situation – contact a licensed septic contractor immediately.</p>

                            <div class="urgency-indicator">
                                <i class="fas fa-biohazard"></i> Environmental Hazard - Call Professionals Now
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="warning-sign">
                        <div class="warning-header">
                            <div class="warning-number">4</div>
                            <h3 class="warning-title">Sewage Backup in Your Home</h3>
                        </div>
                        <div class="warning-content">
                            <p>This is the warning sign no homeowner wants to experience, but it's often the wake-up call that finally gets attention. Sewage backing up into your home through floor drains, toilets, or utility sinks means your septic system has reached critical failure.</p>

                            <div class="image-placeholder" style="height: 250px; margin: 25px 0;">
                                <i class="fas fa-toilet"></i>
                                <span>Sewage Backup in Home Bathroom</span>
                            </div>

                            <p><strong>Where backups typically occur:</strong></p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Basement floor drains (usually the first sign)</li>
                                <li>Lowest-level toilets and showers</li>
                                <li>Utility room sinks and washing machine drains</li>
                                <li>Bathroom fixtures on the main floor</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p><strong>The progression:</strong> Backups rarely happen suddenly. They typically follow this pattern:</p>
                            <ol style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Intermittent gurgling sounds from drains</li>
                                <li>Slow drainage that worsens over time</li>
                                <li>Water appearing in floor drains during heavy usage</li>
                                <li>Full sewage backup during peak usage times</li>
                                <li>Continuous backup requiring immediate action</li>
                            </ol>

                            <p><strong>Health and safety concerns:</strong> Raw sewage contains dangerous bacteria, viruses, and parasites including E. coli, hepatitis, and salmonella. Exposure can cause serious illness, especially in children, elderly individuals, and those with compromised immune systems.</p>

                            <p><strong>Immediate response protocol:</strong></p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Stop all water usage immediately</li>
                                <li>Keep family members and pets away from affected areas</li>
                                <li>Contact a septic emergency service</li>
                                <li>Document damage for insurance purposes</li>
                                <li>Begin professional cleanup and sanitization</li>
                            </ul>

                            <div class="urgency-indicator">
                                <i class="fas fa-phone"></i> Emergency Response Required - Call Now
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="warning-sign">
                        <div class="warning-header">
                            <div class="warning-number">5</div>
                            <h3 class="warning-title">High Nitrate Levels in Well Water</h3>
                        </div>
                        <div class="warning-content">
                            <p>If your home uses well water, elevated nitrate levels can indicate that your septic system is contaminating your groundwater. This silent threat often goes undetected until routine water testing reveals dangerous contamination levels.</p>

                            <div class="image-placeholder" style="height: 250px; margin: 25px 0;">
                                <i class="fas fa-flask"></i>
                                <span>Water Testing Kit Showing High Nitrate Levels</span>
                            </div>

                            <p><strong>Understanding the connection:</strong> When septic systems fail or operate inefficiently, they release untreated wastewater into the soil. This contaminated water can travel through soil and rock, eventually reaching groundwater sources and contaminating wells.</p>

                            <p><strong>Safe vs. dangerous nitrate levels:</strong></p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Safe level: Below 10 mg/L (milligrams per liter)</li>
                                <li>Concerning level: 10-15 mg/L</li>
                                <li>Dangerous level: Above 15 mg/L</li>
                                <li>Critical level: Above 20 mg/L (immediate action required)</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p><strong>Health risks of nitrate contamination:</strong></p>
                            <ul style="margin: 15px 0; padding-left: 20px;">
                                <li>Blue baby syndrome in infants (potentially fatal)</li>
                                <li>Increased cancer risk with long-term exposure</li>
                                <li>Pregnancy complications</li>
                                <li>Thyroid problems</li>
                                <li>Digestive issues and nausea</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p><strong>Testing recommendations:</strong> If you have a private well, test your water annually for nitrates. If you notice any other septic warning signs, test immediately. Professional water testing costs $50-100 but could save your family's health and thousands in medical bills.</p>

                            <p><strong>What elevated nitrates tell you:</strong> High nitrate levels indicate your septic system is failing to properly treat wastewater before it enters the environment. This suggests problems with the drain field, improper system sizing, or system overload.</p>

                            <div class="urgency-indicator">
                                <i class="fas fa-medkit"></i> Health Risk - Test Water Immediately
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="lead-magnet-box">
                    <div class="emergency-icon">
                        <i class="fas fa-ambulance"></i>
                    </div>
                    <h3 class="lead-magnet-title">Emergency Septic Survival Guide</h3>
                    <p class="lead-magnet-subtitle">Septic problem at 2AM? This quick-reference guide helps you take action fast—without making it worse.</p>
                    <a href="#" class="cta-button">
                        <i class="fas fa-download"></i> Download Free Emergency Guide
                    </a>
                </div>

                <div class="action-section">
                    <h2 class="action-title">What to Do When You Spot These Warning Signs</h2>
                    <p class="action-text">
                        The key to avoiding septic disaster is taking immediate, appropriate action when you notice these warning signs. Here's your step-by-step response plan that has saved homeowners thousands of dollars in emergency repairs.
                    </p>

                    <div class="image-placeholder" style="height: 300px; margin: 30px auto;">
                        <i class="fas fa-clipboard-list"></i>
                        <span>Emergency Response Checklist Infographic</span>
                    </div>

                    <div style="text-align: left; max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto;">
                        <h3 style="color: #2c3e50; margin-bottom: 20px;">Immediate Actions (Within 24 Hours):</h3>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #555; padding-left: 20px;">
                            <li><strong>Reduce water usage by 50%:</strong> Limit showers, laundry, and dishwashing to prevent system overload</li>
                            <li><strong>Document everything:</strong> Take photos of wet spots, standing water, or backup areas for your septic contractor</li>
                            <li><strong>Avoid chemical solutions:</strong> Don't use drain cleaners, bleach, or antibacterial products that can kill beneficial bacteria</li>
                            <li><strong>Contact a licensed professional:</strong> Don't wait for the problem to "resolve itself" – early intervention saves money</li>
                            <li><strong>Keep family safe:</strong> Avoid contact with standing water or sewage, and ensure pets stay away from affected areas</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3 style="color: #2c3e50; margin: 30px 0 20px 0;">Professional Assessment (Within 48-72 Hours):</h3>
                        <ul style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #555; padding-left: 20px;">
                            <li><strong>System inspection:</strong> A qualified technician should assess your tank, distribution box, and drain field</li>
                            <li><strong>Pumping evaluation:</strong> Determine if your tank needs pumping (most tanks require pumping every 3-5 years)</li>
                            <li><strong>Flow testing:</strong> Check if wastewater is moving properly through your system</li>
                            <li><strong>Soil evaluation:</strong> Assess drain field condition and soil absorption capacity</li>
                            <li><strong>Repair recommendations:</strong> Get a detailed plan for addressing any identified issues</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="stat-box" style="margin: 40px 0;">
                        <span class="stat-number">73%</span>
                        <div class="stat-text">of septic system failures could have been prevented with proper maintenance and early intervention</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

