                <div class="content-section">
                    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                    
                    <div style="margin: 40px 0;">
                        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 15px; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 20px; box-shadow: 0 5px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.08); border-left: 5px solid #667eea;">
                            <h3 style="color: #2c3e50; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-question-circle" style="color: #667eea; margin-right: 10px;"></i>
                                How often should I have my septic tank pumped?
                            </h3>
                            <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">Most residential septic tanks should be pumped every 3-5 years, depending on household size and usage. A family of four with a 1,000-gallon tank typically needs pumping every 3-4 years. However, if you notice any of the warning signs mentioned above, don't wait for your scheduled pumping date.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 15px; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 20px; box-shadow: 0 5px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.08); border-left: 5px solid #667eea;">
                            <h3 style="color: #2c3e50; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-question-circle" style="color: #667eea; margin-right: 10px;"></i>
                                Can I fix septic problems myself?
                            </h3>
                            <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">While you can handle basic maintenance like reducing water usage and avoiding harmful chemicals, actual septic repairs should always be handled by licensed professionals. DIY septic repairs can be dangerous, may violate local codes, and often make problems worse. However, early detection and proper maintenance can prevent most major issues.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 15px; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 20px; box-shadow: 0 5px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.08); border-left: 5px solid #667eea;">
                            <h3 style="color: #2c3e50; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-question-circle" style="color: #667eea; margin-right: 10px;"></i>
                                What should I do if sewage backs up into my home?
                            </h3>
                            <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">Immediately stop all water usage, keep family and pets away from the affected area, and call a septic emergency service. Do not attempt cleanup until the source is fixed. Sewage backup requires professional remediation to ensure proper sanitization and prevent health hazards.</p>
                        </div>

                        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 15px; padding: 30px; margin-bottom: 20px; box-shadow: 0 5px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.08); border-left: 5px solid #667eea;">
                            <h3 style="color: #2c3e50; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                                <i class="fas fa-question-circle" style="color: #667eea; margin-right: 10px;"></i>
                                Are septic additives worth using?
                            </h3>
                            <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">Quality bacterial additives can help maintain your system's bacterial balance, especially after antibiotic use or chemical exposure. However, they're not a substitute for proper maintenance and pumping. Avoid additives claiming to eliminate the need for pumping – these are typically scams that can damage your system.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

